c mount is quite possibly going to find a few <br />other cases like this. <br /><br />IOW, _maybe_ you hit the only case that is ever going to be an issue for <br />sync mounts, and maybe you didn't. In my eternal quest to never actually <br />test anything myself, I'm hoping you can try some writing (and <br />over-writing) of files, since writes to the filesystem is where the whole <br />"sync" thing is going to show up (both metadata ie file creation and <br />removal, and "real" data ie normal write/truncate calls).<br /><br />			Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
